# Clean Code Architecture

Dependencies **always point inward** toward the domain kernel.

## Layer Map

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Routers (HTTP binding)                 │  ← outermost
├─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Feature Services (use-case logic)      │
├─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Infrastructure (protocol impls)        │
├─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Shared Kernel (entities, protocols)    │  ← innermost, pure
└─────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Shared Kernel (`src/shared/kernel/`)

Entities, repository protocols (ABCs), and pure domain logic. **No external dependencies.** No I/O, no framework imports, no side effects.

```python
# Pure entity — just data
@dataclass
class Order:
    id: str
    customer_id: str
    status: str
    items: list[OrderItem]

# Repository protocol — defines WHAT, not HOW
class OrderRepository(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    async def get(self, order_id: str) -> Order | None: ...
```

## Feature Services (`src/features/**/service.py`)

Use-case logic. Dependencies injected via constructor. Depend on kernel protocols, never on concrete implementations.

```python
class CreateOrderService:
    def __init__(self, orders: OrderRepository, notifications: NotificationGateway):
        self._orders = orders
        self._notifications = notifications

    async def execute(self, cmd: CreateOrderCommand) -> Order:
        order = Order(id=generate_id(), ...)
        await self._orders.save(order)
        await self._notifications.send(order.customer_id, "Order created")
        return order
```

## Infrastructure (`src/shared/infrastructure/`)

Implements kernel protocols. This is the only layer that knows about MongoDB, HTTP clients, external APIs.

## Routers (`src/features/**/router.py`)

**Thin HTTP binding.** Delegate to one service method. No business logic, no data assembly, no conditional branching.

```python
# GOOD — thin
@router.post("/", response_model=OrderResponse, status_code=201)
async def create_order(body: CreateOrderRequest, request: Request):
    c = request.app.state.container
    return await CreateOrderService(c.order_repo, c.notifier).execute(body.to_command())

# BAD — business logic leaked into router
@router.post("/")
async def create_order(body: CreateOrderRequest, request: Request):
    if body.total > 10000:
        await send_high_value_alert(body)  # This belongs in the service
    order = await repo.save(...)
    return order
```

## Clean Code Principles

- **Small functions** — each does one thing. If you need a comment to explain a block, extract it.
- **Clear names** — `get_active_orders_for_customer` not `get_data`. The name IS the documentation.
- **Single responsibility** — a service handles one use case. If it coordinates multiple features, it is an orchestrator.
- **Constructor injection** — dependencies arrive via `__init__`, never imported globally or created inline.
